    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7e79c656_94151528",
        "filename": "util/win/process_info.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T21:30:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e These are malloc-semantic allocations, not Heap*-semantic allocations.  The difference is that in supporting builds, they return nullptr instead of terminating the process.\n\nWell, in some builds the allocation will be routed one way, and in others, it’ll be routed a different way? All the more reason to match UncheckedMalloc() with a newly provided UncheckedMallocFree() that always picks the “right” way to free an allocation depending on how UncheckedMalloc() is configured.",
      "parentUuid": "dd245d00_ddfc96ef",
      "revId": "7f90922bda75a748794096fb4205c84e37525faf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0eec2d98_52cd3e44",
        "filename": "util/win/process_info.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1177549
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-08T15:39:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "No, the allocation will always be supplied by the malloc heap, and should always be freed with free. The base interface has no special way to free these, and it would be a very weird deviation from the base interface to do differently here.\nThe only difference between this function and malloc, is that in some builds (like Chrome), the standard malloc is diverted in and implemented in such a way that it will never return nullptr, but will instead terminate the program.\nIn such builds, this function will still return \"malloc\"-ed memory, but will return nullptr if the heap or the system are fresh out of bytes.\n\nI\u0027ve added a comment to the new base file to make this clear.",
      "parentUuid": "7e79c656_94151528",
      "revId": "7f90922bda75a748794096fb4205c84e37525faf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "509fb6ae_69b9bb36",
        "filename": "util/win/process_info.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1144260
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-08T18:06:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m lost.\n\nWhat would UncheckedMallocFree() do differently than base::UncheckedMalloc() does now? To me, the fact that it\u0027s called \"M\"alloc makes it clear that it needs to be free()d.\n\nMark, are you saying you would like a base function that returns a templated object that has the deallocation function pre-attached?",
      "parentUuid": "0eec2d98_52cd3e44",
      "revId": "7f90922bda75a748794096fb4205c84e37525faf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a0188583_cc3aca56",
        "filename": "util/win/process_info.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-08T18:46:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I\u0027m lost.\n\u003e \n\u003e What would UncheckedMallocFree() do differently than base::UncheckedMalloc() does now? To me, the fact that it\u0027s called \"M\"alloc makes it clear that it needs to be free()d.\n\u003e \n\u003e Mark, are you saying you would like a base function that returns a templated object that has the deallocation function pre-attached?\n\nAll I’m saying is that if you allocate via UncheckedMalloc(), it’d be nice for that to be mated with UncheckedMallocFree(). Maybe blocks that you get from UncheckedMalloc() can be released with free(), and maybe that’s easy to guarantee on Windows. But in general, I think that any allocation interface should have its own matching releasing interface.",
      "parentUuid": "509fb6ae_69b9bb36",
      "revId": "7f90922bda75a748794096fb4205c84e37525faf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0312e79e_dd597abb",
        "filename": "util/win/process_info.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1177549
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-08T18:57:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "As we discussed offline, these allocs should be deallocated with free(). This is by contract, and is tested in base unittests.\nI can add documentation to the header in Chromium, to make this unambiguous.",
      "parentUuid": "a0188583_cc3aca56",
      "revId": "7f90922bda75a748794096fb4205c84e37525faf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7c5ad4ef_47aa1dd7",
        "filename": "util/win/process_info.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1144260
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-08T18:58:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Ah, gotcha! My misunderstanding was what UncheckedMallocFree() would actually do, because I had trouble processing the name as the \"Free for Malloc\", rather than something that was somehow bundling the two.\n\nSo that seems like a good idea to me too, but I don\u0027t like calling it UncheckedMallocFree(), unless the other one is ... uh, UncheckedMallocAlloc() or UncheckedMallocMalloc(). Hmm...\n\nI guess I\u0027d vote for UncheckedFree() as the pair to UncheckedMalloc(), given that they\u0027re together in  base:: and in the semi-namespace of \"Unchecked\" as well.",
      "parentUuid": "a0188583_cc3aca56",
      "revId": "7f90922bda75a748794096fb4205c84e37525faf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ee93b538_f2f5adfb",
        "filename": "util/win/process_info.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1177549
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-08T19:54:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hey guys, this ship has long left, and the allocs from UncheckedMalloc are firmly in the malloc  allocation domain. This is tested https://cs.chromium.org/chromium/src/base/process/memory_unittest.cc?q\u003dUncheckedMalloc\u0026l\u003d448 in the base unittests, and is firmly part of the contract.\nThis is also squarely to support the original malloc() allocation semantics, with respect of not scuttling the process on OOM, but rather returning nullptr.\nSkia, as a case in point, looks to freely intermingle malloc/UncheckedMalloc allocations, and my bet is that it\u0027d be hard and ultimately a waste of time to tease that apart.\n\nThis isn\u0027t an allocation domain, was never intended to be a new allocation domain, of which Chrome already has too many. Adding an alias to free() for these allocs is IMHO just going to add further confusion.\n\nIMHO this CL is also not the appropriate venue to debate long-decided semantics of Chrome base.\n\nI can update the docs in process/memory.h to make sure there\u0027s no question as to the intent that the memory should be free()\u0027d, but at this point I\u0027d really like to see whether this general approach is viable to quench the OOM problems in Chrome\u0027s crash handler.",
      "parentUuid": "7c5ad4ef_47aa1dd7",
      "revId": "7f90922bda75a748794096fb4205c84e37525faf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "34e5d795_ca1741cf",
        "filename": "util/win/process_info.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
